body:
Moodboard | Kylux Assassins AU

[ He doesn’t care about mens with guns which promised to do “something” tomorrow. There only terribly painful “Now.”

- You smell like smoke, - comes up from the back, hugs, sticks his forehead in the shoulder - hair tickles the line of the scar on the neck - leaves stains from it’s cleaners on the fabric - now there is only a get rid of t-shirt. You can just now. - Ugh.

But snuggles closer, smiles, sneaks his fingers to the skin. He knows that Hux is now smiling, he closes his sly eyes and quite smiles - apparently he is taking revenge for the motel, for the bathroom, for the web, for the cigarette butts.

- And from you carries “Ballistol”, so that’s why I prefer to work with knives. No patience is enough to mess with all this shite.

- Watch your language - gently, with a mockery, in the very neck. “Don’t hurt my rifle, Ren.”

- Oh, I still didn’t have enough to compete with it for you. ]

blog.name: radioactivepeasant
blog.title: Nobody Panic!
blog.description:
Adventures in fandom and creative writing

Here, you'll find a lot of fandom-related posts...and a heck of a lot of writing. So much writing. I do writing prompts just about every weekday, Monday to Friday.

What you're not going to find are posts that insult others or put people down. There's enough of that in the real world: I don't need any on my blog, thanks.

tags: yes this is literally wedge and hobbie vs labyrinth
i was listening to the soundtrack earlier
the king of the ruins is space david bowie
some of the goblins are yoda's species because that seems logical to me
but can rogue squadron win a dance-off against jareth?
body:
Fic Prompts: Star Wars Wednesday

He wasn’t supposed to be doing this.

He really, really wasn’t supposed to be doing this.

The Rogues were there to provide an escort and backup, and they needed to be ready to go at a moment’s notice. And yet here they were, navigating the winding, dusty streets because of a kid who looked like she was in trouble.

“I just have a bad feeling,” he’d said.

Hobbie had snorted at that. “You sound like Skywalker,” he’d teased.

Wedge caught up to the girl just as the city became scrub land, leading to a very unfriendly looking mass of rubble. She was small for a Devaronian, no more than fourteen at a guess. She bit her lip and stared into the ruins, then checked a very small blaster at her side.

“Hey, kid,” Wedge called out, “You okay?”

The girl jumped and eyed them warily. “You can’t stop me,” she said.

Wedge held up his hands. “Um…stop you from doing what, exactly? All I know is you look kinda worried.”

“We’re with the New Republic,” Hobbie added, “If you or your parents need help-”

At the mention of parents, the girl winced. “Don’t tell them,” she burst out suddenly, “I didn’t mean to do it!”

Wedge and Hobbie exchanged glances. “Uh…”

After conspicuously examining the blasters on their belts, the girl took a step closer. “Are you good at fighting?”

“Yep,” Hobbie answered flatly.

“We’re not too bad,” Wedge shrugged.

“What about mazes, are you any good at those?” She eyed them critically. “I guess I could stand on your shoulders to see over the walls.”

Hobbie cleared his throat. “Kid, are you going to tell us what’s going on? Because you sound like you want to recruit us for something.”

After an awkward pause, the girl relented. “I’m Zarah,” she sighed, “And I have to fight the King of the Ruins and beat him before sunrise.”

“King of the Ruins?” asked Hobbie.

“Sunrise? Why sunrise?” asked Wedge. “In fact, why does a kid have to fight this guy at all?”

Zarah fidgeted, looking guilty. Then she unexpectedly cried, “I wished my baby sister away – I didn’t mean to, I didn’t think it would work – but now the King of the Ruins won’t give her back unless I defeat him, but I know he’s going to cheat and send monsters!”

The two Rogues took a moment to digest that information. Then, softly, Hobbie muttered, “…the kriff?”

Well, a baby at risk was a baby at risk, “magic” maze or not. And if there really was some random guy kidnapping people and taking them to the ruins, the local authorities probably needed some details about it. Wedge sent a message back to the other Rogues, warning them that something potentially dangerous had come up, then sighed and followed Zarah into the ruins.

Why did he end up in scrapes like this whenever Luke wasn’t there?

Star Wars: Age Of The Republic Special #1 (2019)

The baddest Jedi in the galaxy has a score to settle — MACE WINDU returns in...
caption:
Star Wars: Age Of The Republic Special #1 (2019)

The baddest Jedi in the galaxy has a score to settle — MACE WINDU returns in an action-packed adventure from OLD MAN HAWKEYE’S Ethan Sacks! You can run, but can you hide from the twin lightsabers of Sith assassin ASAJJ VENTRESS? Feel her fury in a tale expertly woven by veteran STAR WARS comic scribe Jody Houser (THRAWN, THE AMAZING SPIDER-MAN: RENEW YOUR VOWS). You can take the clone out of the war but you can never take the war out of the clone — CAPTAIN REX dusts off his blaster and enters the fray in a story by X-MEN: GOLD author Marc Guggenheim.

Story: Marc Guggenheim, Jody Houser, Ethan Sacks , art: Carlos Gomez, Paolo Villanelli, Caspar Wijngaard

summary: I think one of my favorite things about the novelization of Star Wars (A New Hope) is the interactions between Luke and his...
body: I think one of my favorite things about the novelization of Star Wars (A New Hope) is the interactions between Luke and his friends on Tattooine, and his running into his old friend Biggs on their home planet while Biggs was on leave. To me, this piece–which was unfortunately left out of the film version–gives more meaning to Luke’s life on Tattooine, and to his next reunion with Biggs on Yavin IV. There are a lot of other neat things about the novelization, as well. I recommend reading it to any Star Wars fan.

trail.content: I think one of my favorite things about the novelization of Star Wars (A New Hope) is the interactions between Luke and his friends on Tattooine, and his running into his old friend Biggs on their home planet while Biggs was on leave. To me, this piece–which was unfortunately left out of the film version–gives more meaning to Luke’s life on Tattooine, and to his next reunion with Biggs on Yavin IV. There are a lot of other neat things about the novelization, as well. I recommend reading it to any Star Wars fan.

caption:

characters [1/10] - darth zannah

“i wondered why you chose this place to meet. i thought it might have some symbolic meaning for you. the last time we were here you were too weak to even stand. you were helpless, and you thought i had betrayed you to the jedi. you said you would rather die than be a prisoner for the rest of your life. you wanted me to take your life. but i refused.”
“you knew i still had things to teach you. you swore you would not kill me until you had learned all my secrets.”
“that day is here. i have surpassed you, bane. now i am the master.”
